3 Chocolate Covered Strawberries Mistakes to Avoid!
These are the three most common mistakes I see people
making when making chocolate covered strawberries
so you can avoid them and get the same quality chocolate covered strawberries as you would in a store.
The first mistake I see people making is that they don't acid wash their strawberries.
The strawberries might look perfect, but they're full of mold spores all the way around.
In order to kill those mold spores, rinse them in a bath of one cup water and one cup white vinegar for about 15 minutes.
This will prevent your strawberries from going mushy and gooey after they're dipped in the chocolate.
The second mistake I see people making is that they don't properly dry their strawberries.
There's still so much moisture on the outside.
So what you have to do is take your strawberries,
place them on a towel and toss them into the fridge to air dry.
The third mistake I see people making is that they don't thin out their chocolate.
There's nothing worse than having a chocolate covered strawberry, you bite into it and it's this thick shell of chocolate.
You want it to be nice, thin, and crispy.
Now it's going to melt a little bit more evenly and it's going to be a thinner consistency, which is better for dipping your strawberries.
